1. Imports and Setup

    import tensorflow as tf – Imports the TensorFlow library, the core framework for building and training neural networks.

    import numpy as np – Imports NumPy, used for efficient numerical operations on arrays (here, for character mapping and indexing).

    import os – Imports the operating system module (not used directly in the code, but often included for path handling; it’s harmless).

2. Download and Load the Text Data

    path_to_file = tf.keras.utils.get_file(...) – Downloads the Shakespeare text file from a given URL and saves it locally. The function returns the local file path.

    text = open(path_to_file, 'rb').read().decode(encoding='utf-8') – Opens the file in binary mode ('rb'), reads the raw bytes, then decodes them to a UTF‑8 string. This gives us the entire play text as a single Python string.

    print(f"Corpus length: {len(text)} characters") – Prints the total number of characters in the text, giving an idea of the dataset size.

3. Create Character Mappings

    vocab = sorted(set(text)) – Creates a set of all unique characters in the text (letters, punctuation, spaces, etc.), then sorts them to produce a deterministic list. This is our vocabulary.

    vocab_size = len(vocab) – Stores the number of unique characters (e.g., ~65 for Shakespeare’s text).

    print(f"Unique characters: {vocab_size}") – Prints the vocabulary size.

    char2idx = {u: i for i, u in enumerate(vocab)} – Builds a dictionary that maps each character to a unique integer index (e.g., 'a' → 0, 'b' → 1).

    idx2char = np.array(vocab) – Converts the vocabulary list into a NumPy array so we can later map an integer index back to its character using array indexing.

    text_as_int = np.array([char2idx[c] for c in text]) – Converts the entire text string into a NumPy array of integers, where each character is replaced by its corresponding index from char2idx. This is the numeric representation of the whole corpus.

4. Create Training Sequences with tf.data

    SEQ_LENGTH = 100 – Defines the length of each input sequence (number of characters the model sees at once).

    BATCH_SIZE = 64 – Number of sequences in each training batch.

    BUFFER_SIZE = 10000 – Size of the shuffle buffer (how many elements to load into memory for shuffling).

    char_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices(text_as_int) – Creates a TensorFlow Dataset object that yields each integer one by one from the text_as_int array. This is a stream of individual characters.

    sequences = char_dataset.batch(SEQ_LENGTH + 1, drop_remainder=True) – Batches the character stream into chunks of length 101 (SEQ_LENGTH+1). drop_remainder=True discards any incomplete final batch. Each chunk will be used to create an input‑target pair.

    def split_input_target(chunk): – Defines a helper function that takes a chunk of length 101 and returns two tensors: the first 100 characters as input, and the last 100 characters as target. For every position t, the model sees input at t and learns to predict the character at t+1.

    dataset = sequences.map(split_input_target) – Applies the split function to every chunk in the dataset, resulting in a dataset of (input_sequence, target_sequence) pairs.

    dataset = dataset.shuffle(BUFFER_SIZE).batch(BATCH_SIZE, drop_remainder=True).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE) –

        .shuffle(BUFFER_SIZE) randomly shuffles the sequence pairs using a buffer of 10,000 elements (improves training randomness).

        .batch(BATCH_SIZE, drop_remainder=True) groups the shuffled pairs into mini‑batches of 64; drops the last incomplete batch.

        .prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE) overlaps data preprocessing and model execution for better performance.

5. Build the Model

    EMBEDDING_DIM = 256 – Dimension of the embedding vector for each character.

    GRU_UNITS = 1024 – Number of units (neurons) in the GRU layer.

    model = tf.keras.Sequential([ ... ]) – Creates a sequential model, stacking layers in order.

    Embedding(vocab_size, EMBEDDING_DIM, batch_input_shape=[BATCH_SIZE, None]) –

        This layer converts integer indices into dense vectors of size 256.

        batch_input_shape fixes the batch size to 64 and allows variable sequence length (None). This helps with performance.

    GRU(GRU_UNITS, return_sequences=True, stateful=False, dropout=0.2) –

        A Gated Recurrent Unit layer with 1024 units.

        return_sequences=True – returns the full sequence of outputs (not just the last one) because we need predictions at every time step.

        stateful=False – the GRU does not preserve its internal state between batches (standard for this type of training).

        dropout=0.2 – applies 20% dropout to the input connections, helping prevent overfitting.

    Dense(vocab_size, activation='softmax') – A fully connected layer with one output per character in the vocabulary, using softmax to produce a probability distribution over the next character.

    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy']) – Configures the model for training:

        adam optimizer (adaptive learning rate).

        sparse_categorical_crossentropy – suitable when targets are integer class labels (not one‑hot).

        tracks accuracy during training.

    model.summary() – Prints a table showing layer names, output shapes, and number of trainable parameters.

6. Train the Model

    EPOCHS = 20 – Number of times to iterate over the entire dataset.

    history = model.fit(dataset, epochs=EPOCHS) – Trains the model on the batched dataset for 20 epochs. The history object stores training loss and accuracy values for each epoch (can be used for plotting later).

7. Text Generation with Temperature

    def generate_text(model, start_string, num_generate=500, temperature=1.0): – Defines a function that generates new text character by character.

    input_indices = [char2idx[s] for s in start_string if s in char2idx] – Converts the starting string (e.g., "ROMEO: ") into a list of integer indices, ignoring any characters not in the vocabulary.

    if not input_indices: input_indices = [char2idx[' ']] – If the start string is empty or contains only unknown characters, fallback to a space character.

    input_indices = tf.constant(input_indices, dtype=tf.int64) – Converts the list to a TensorFlow constant.

    input_indices = tf.expand_dims(input_indices, 0) – Adds a batch dimension, making the shape (1, len_start) because the model expects a batch axis.

    generated = list(start_string) – Initialises the output list with the starting string characters.

    for _ in range(num_generate): – Loop to generate num_generate new characters.

    predictions = model(input_indices) – Runs the model on the current input sequence; returns logits (before softmax) of shape (1, current_seq_len, vocab_size).

    predictions = predictions[:, -1, :] – Keeps only the predictions for the last time step, giving shape (1, vocab_size) – these are the probabilities for the next character.

    predictions = predictions / temperature – Divides the logits by the temperature parameter. Higher temperature (e.g., 1.5) makes the distribution more uniform (more random); lower temperature (0.5) makes it more peaked (more conservative, picking the most likely character).

    sampled_index = tf.random.categorical(predictions, num_samples=1) – Samples one index from the categorical distribution defined by the scaled logits. tf.random.categorical takes logits (not probabilities) and returns an integer.

    sampled_index = sampled_index.numpy()[0][0] – Converts the Tensor to a NumPy array and extracts the scalar integer value.

    predicted_char = idx2char[sampled_index] – Maps the integer back to a character using the idx2char array.

    generated.append(predicted_char) – Appends the new character to the generated text list.

    input_indices = tf.concat([input_indices[:, 1:], [[sampled_index]]], axis=-1) – Updates the input sequence for the next step:

        input_indices[:, 1:] drops the first character of the current sequence.

        [[sampled_index]] adds the newly predicted character at the end.

        tf.concat along the last axis creates a new sequence of the same length (sliding window).

    return ''.join(generated) – Joins all characters into a single string and returns it.

